b'What can travelers do to prevent HIV? https://t.co/JqYZ9HxlxH  #WAD2018  Before you go:  1)Talk w/ ur Dr. abt \xe2\x80\x9cPrEP\xe2\x80\x9d (or pre-exposure prophylaxis)- Travelers who are at high risk for HIV infection can get a daily pill that prevents HIV, known as \xe2\x80\x9cPrEP.\xe2\x80\x9d  2) Get tested. https://t.co/LMNn1RdFC2'

b'Where is HIV more common? HIV infection affects people around the \xf0\x9f\x97\xba\xef\xb8\x8f. Sub-Saharan Africa remains the most affected, but other regions sig. affected by HIV include Asia &; the Pacific, Latin Am &; the Caribbean, &; Est. EU &; Central Asia. https://t.co/JqYZ9HxlxH  #WAD2018 https://t.co/PPdR3YikIY'

b'How is HIV spread? It is spread through certain body fluids: blood, sexual fluids &; breast milk. Most people get HIV from having unprotected sex w/ some1 who has HIV, or from sharing needles or other drug injection equipment w/ some1 who has HIV: https://t.co/JqYZ9HxlxH  #WAD2018 https://t.co/vhOJ5Ip9GU'

b'Health care workers who are practicing outside the United States should be prepared to initiate postexposure prophylaxis in the event of an occupational exposure to bodily fluids from patients with known or potential HIV transmission. https://t.co/SVGYg3wVAv https://t.co/pI1ZXj0cDw'

b'What travelers are at risk? Travelers are generally at low risk for getting HIV unless they act in ways that could put them at risk, such as having unprotected sex or sharing needles with people who are or might be infected with HIV. https://t.co/JqYZ9HxlxH  #WAD2018 https://t.co/3lLSpU2zBb'

b'What is HIV? It is a virus that attacks the body's immune system. Because people with HIV infection may appear healthy for many years, you often can't tell if someone has HIV.  https://t.co/JqYZ9HxlxH  #WAD2018 https://t.co/0KFCW5xsTG'

b'What should I do if I have pneumococcal symptoms after I traveled?   Call your doctor and tell him or her where you have traveled. https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV #WorldPneumoniaDay #WPD2018 https://t.co/2PJl53GkOx'

b'How is pneumococcal disease prevented?   There is a shot that can protect you. Also, when you are traveling, wash your hands often. https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV #WorldPneumoniaDay #WPD2018 https://t.co/xhx6yzvs16'

b'Who is at risk for pneumococcal disease?   People at higher-risk include adults 65+ &; kids <2 years, those w/ chronic illnesses such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease, lung disease, or HIV/AIDS or people who smoke cigarettes. https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV #WorldPneumoniaDay #WPD2018 https://t.co/JysjRClfEG'

b'When &; where is pneumococcal disease?   It occurs world-wide, but is more common in developing countries. In most places it occurs during the winter/early spring but occurs year-round in the tropics. https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV #WorldPneumoniaDay #WPD2018 https://t.co/Jh8YaWH08n'

b'What are the symptoms?   Depends on where the infection is- fever, cough, chest pain, stiff neck, disorientation, light sensitivity, joint pain, chills, ear pain, sleeplessness, irritability. Severe cases incl: hearing loss, brain damage, &; death. https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV https://t.co/VdPjVvXbbW'

b'How is pneumococcus bacteria spread?   It is spread through coughing, sneezing, &; close contact with an infected person. https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV #WorldPneumoniaDay #WPD2018 https://t.co/gxb3F8Lr11'

b'What is pneumococcal disease?   It is a variety of infections caused by bacteria, including: pneumonia (lungs), ear, sinus, meningitis (covering around the brain &; spinal cord), &; bacteremia (blood stream). https://t.co/XcXSPeJYvV #WorldPneumoniaDay #WPD2018 https://t.co/JNVm6h3lAH'
